113241573.review:
tl;dr: Owlboy is a hard to recommend game, It's a great concept, but some oversights almost ruins the game.

I hard about this game from videogamedunkey and decided to try It, here is what I liked about the game:
- Amazing pixelart, the characters and animations are really well made;
- Music is good;
- The world/plot is okay, a lot is not explained, but overall It's interesting;
- The main gameplay of flying around and using your friends to attack is good.

Here is the bad part:
- No map, this one almost ruins the game, this game is a bit of a metroidvania and there is no map, which makes It really hard to navigate some dungeons;
- Dark areas are a pain in the ass, some areas of the game are dark so you have to navigate with little to no light;
- The camera, some areas of the game is like a 2D Zelda where the camera moves from on square to the next, sometimes you get hit because the camera move to a new screen with an enemy near by;
- There is an annoying/hard mini game that you have to complete if you want to 100% the game.

Overall I would say the game is okay, not the worst indie game, but there are better options.

54787543.review:
Super charming game with an interesting story and lovely art. One beef I have is with the difficulty, the exploration is chill most of the time but there are some weird difficulty spikes which feel unbalanced. I could see a non-judgmental assist mode like Celeste's being used a lot here.

In case the devs look at these, the boguin cannon minigame is a nice idea but has LOTS of (fixable) problems:

- There is no contrast between the scenery and Otus, the background is very noisy and there are even some clouds on the foreground, it is really hard to keep track of the character;
- The camera sometimes lags behind a lot making the whole minigame about memorization;
- The tank controls with the quick rotations make 0 sense, they are not intuitive at all;
- There is no quick restart, on collision there should be a key prompt to put Otus back to the first falling part when we regain control after the blast, with just a minimal fade in/out.
